    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-09-01T09:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-09-01T09:54:00-05:00" n="685"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d685">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.7962/29: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moose</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-01T18:00:00+03:06"
                            >September 1, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 3—9:39 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>56. My 55, August 29, 6 p.m. In further conversation with British Minister Shaikh
                    Yusuf stated that route specified between Birk and Bahrein is merely the
                    northernmost of permissible routes to Bahrein and that planes may choose their
                    own routes south of that alignment so long as they do not pass near Suleil, also
                    written Sulaiyl.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Cairo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moose</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
